
Exp-07
OBJECTIVE

Understand how to containerize a basic application

Learn how to build Docker images

Learn how to run containers using port mapping

Verify application output via browser


Exp-07

SOFTWARE REQUIREMENTS

Docker (Docker Desktop for Windows/macOS or Docker Engine for Linux)

OS: Windows 10/11 with WSL2 / Ubuntu / macOS

Git installed

Internet connection

Optional editor: VS Code


Exp-07

ðŸš€ LAB PROCEDURE
1. Clone the Getting-Started App Repository

Run the command:

git clone https://github.com/docker/getting-started-app.git


This clones the official sample app from Docker Hubâ€™s GitHub repository.


Exp-07

2. View Folder Structure

Your folder should contain:

getting-started-app/
â”‚â”€â”€ .dockerignore
â”‚â”€â”€ package.json
â”‚â”€â”€ README.md
â”‚â”€â”€ spec/
â”‚â”€â”€ src/
â”‚â”€â”€ yarn.lock


(Structure shown on page 1 of the PDF.)


Exp-07

3. Create a Dockerfile

Inside the getting-started-app directory, create a file named Dockerfile and add:

FROM node:18-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN yarn install --production
CMD ["node", "src/index.js"]
EXPOSE 3000


Exp-07

Then navigate into the project folder:

cd /path/to/getting-started-app

4. Build the Docker Image

Run:

docker build -t getting-started-app .


Make sure you use a regular hyphen - (not a long dash).


Exp-07

5. Verify Image Creation

Check if the image exists:

docker images


Output will show something like (from PDF):

REPOSITORY            TAG      IMAGE ID        SIZE
getting-started-app   latest   3d2d9fbba095    346MB


Exp-07

6. Run the Application Container

Start container with port-mapping:

docker run -dp 127.0.0.1:3000:3000 getting-started-app


-d â†’ run in background

-p â†’ map host port 3000 to container port 3000

PDF example shows the container running successfully.


Exp-07

7. Verify Output in Browser

Open:

http://localhost:3000


You should see the running app (To-Do list interface as shown in PDF).
